In Mono, the following test passes:

```
    var uri = new Uri("/dev/null", UriKind.RelativeOrAbsolute);
    Assert.True(uri.IsAbsoluteUri);
```

With CoreFX, it does not.  Is this a bug or a feature?

I ran into this issue when trying to port `System.Net.Http` to Mono - for instance, the [System.Net.Http.Functional.Tests.HttpClientTest. GetAsync_NoBaseAddress_InvalidUri_ThrowsException](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/src/System.Net.Http/tests/FunctionalTests/HttpClientTest.cs#L160) will fail, which is essentially the following:

```
    [Theory]
    [InlineData("/something.html")]
    public void GetAsync_NoBaseAddress_InvalidUri_ThrowsException(string uri)
    {
        using (HttpClient client = CreateHttpClient())
        {
            Assert.Throws<InvalidOperationException>(() => { client.GetAsync(new Uri(uri, UriKind.RelativeOrAbsolute)); });
        }
    }
```

In [HttpRequestMessage.InitializeValues](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/master/src/System.Net.Http/src/System/Net/Http/HttpRequestMessage.cs#L188), there is the following code:

```
        if ((requestUri != null) && (requestUri.IsAbsoluteUri) && (!HttpUtilities.IsHttpUri(requestUri)))
        {
            throw new ArgumentException(SR.net_http_client_http_baseaddress_required, nameof(requestUri));
        }
```

There are only a handful of tests failing with this

```
    System.Net.Http.Functional.Tests.HttpRequestMessageTest.Ctor_RelativeStringUri_CorrectValues [FAIL]
    System.Net.Http.Functional.Tests.SocketsHttpHandler_HttpCookieProtocolTests.GetAsyncWithRedirect_ReceiveSetCookie_CookieSent [FAIL]
    System.Net.Http.Functional.Tests.SocketsHttpHandler_HttpCookieProtocolTests.GetAsyncWithRedirect_SetCookieContainer_CorrectCookiesSent [FAIL]
    System.Net.Http.Functional.Tests.SocketsHttpHandler_HttpClientTest.GetAsync_NoBaseAddress_InvalidUri_ThrowsException(uri: "/something.html") [FAIL]
```

Is this something that I need to be worried about - as in there's a chance that something else might break due to this incompatibility - or can I just disable those tests for the moment?

In .NET Framework, you could register a default port with `UriParser.Register()`:

```
        [Fact]
        public static void Register_DefaultPort()
        {
            var scheme = "X" + Guid.NewGuid().ToString();
            var parser = new FileStyleUriParser();
            Assert.False(UriParser.IsKnownScheme(scheme), "IsKnownScheme-false");
            UriParser.Register(parser, scheme, 8888);
            Uri uri = new Uri($"{scheme}:///readme.txt");
            Assert.Equal(8888, uri.Port);
        }
```

This currently returns -1 instead of 8888.

Enumerable.Repeat should have an overload with the following signature:

public static System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable<TResult> Repeat<TResult> (TResult element);

The behavior would be repeating the value infinitely to allow composing lazy sequences without having to provide int.MaxValue or similar workarounds (which have the obvious limitation of having a bound).

~~~cs
static class Example
{
    public static IEnumerable<bool> ToBinary(uint i) => Enumerable.Repeat(i)
              .Select((num, shift) => num >> shift)
              .TakeWhile(x => x != 0)
              .Select(x => (x & 1) == 1);
}
~~~

